Consider the data frame iris in R. We are interested in estimating the standard deviation \(\sigma\) of the variable Sepal.Length (ignore the grouping variable Species).

Q: Compute a 90%-confidence interval for \(\sigma\) and interpret the result.

##  setosa    :50

##

alpha <- 0.1

# Simulation function
confint <- function(x){
  
  # Obtain the sample size n
  n <- length(iris$Sepal.Length)
  
  # Obtain the sample standard deviation s
  sx <- sqrt(var(iris$Sepal.Length))
  
  # Calculate the critical values using chi^2 distribution
  c_l <- qchisq(alpha/2,n-1,lower.tail=FALSE)
  c_u <- qchisq(alpha/2,n-1,lower.tail=TRUE)
  
  # Calculate the confidence interval
  lower <- sqrt((n-1) * sx^2 /c_l)
  upper <- sqrt((n-1) * sx^2 /c_u)
  
  # Print the result
  print(paste0("90%-confidence interval for standard deviation is [ ",
        round(lower,6)," , ",round(upper,6)," ]."))
}

# Implement the function
confint(iris$Sepal.Length)
## [1] "90%-confidence interval for standard deviation is [ 0.756583 , 0.91592 ]."

Interpretation: If we compute confidence interval in repeated samples, then \(\sigma\) would be contained in \((1-\alpha)·100 \%\) of the time in confidence interval. Here we calculated an exact confidence interval for \(\sigma\) based on given dataset, which measures the accuracy depending on the distribution.

Q: Explain in 1-2 sentences, when the chosen method of the computation of the confidence interval will control the nominal coverage probability.

A: When the distributional assumption is fulfilled:

\((X_1,...,X_n \sim N(\mu,{\sigma}^2))\)

2 Question 2

In statistics, describing the width of a distribution is a fundamental but rather challenging task.

We consider the inter-quartile range (IQR): \(IQR = Q_3 - Q_1\), with \(Q_1\) and \(Q_3\) being the first (=25% percentile) and third quartile (=75% percentile) as measure of interest.

2.1 First

Q: Using an appropriate resampling method, find the true IQR of the N(0, 1) and Exp(1) distributions. Compare your results with the functions qnorm and qexp. In addition, illustrate the variability of their empirical versions \(\widehat{IQR} = \hat{Q_3} - \hat{Q_1}\) in both distribution models.

A:

# Clear the environment
rm(list = ls())

# Build the function simu_IQR
simu_IQR <- function(Dist,n,nsim,nboot){
  
  # Create some containers
  IQR <- c()
  IQR_var <- c()
  
  # Generate data from different distributions
  if(Dist == "Normal") {
    x <- matrix(rnorm(n*nsim, mean = 0, sd = 1),ncol = nsim)
    IQR_std <- diff(qnorm(c(0.25, 0.75), mean = 0, sd = 1))
  }
  if(Dist == "Exponential") {
    x <- matrix((rexp(n = n*nsim, rate = 1) - 1) / sqrt(1), ncol = nsim)
    IQR_std <- diff(qexp(c(0.25, 0.75),rate = 1))
  }
  
  # Helping Matrix for Non-parametric Bootstrap
  B <- apply(matrix(1:n, ncol = nboot, nrow = n), 2, sample, replace = TRUE)
  
  # Bootstrap
  for(i in 1:nsim){
    xi <- x[,i]
    xstar <- matrix(xi[B], ncol = nboot, nrow = n)
    IQR_star <- apply(xstar,2,IQR)
    IQR[i] <- mean(IQR_star)
    IQR_var[i] <- var(IQR_star)
  }
  
  #Plot a histogram of the distribution of the point estimate
  hist(IQR)
  
  # MSE and Bias as a measure to compare my results
  # with the functions qnorm and qexp
  MSEstar <- mean((IQR - IQR_std)^2)
  Biasstar <- mean(IQR - IQR_std)
  
  
  result <- data.frame(n = n, Dist = Dist, MSE_boot = round(MSEstar,6), Bias_boot = round(Biasstar,6), Var_emp = round(mean(IQR_var),6) ,IQR_boot_mean = round(mean(IQR),6), IQR_std = round(IQR_std,6), nsim = nsim, nboot = nboot)
  result
}

set.seed(1)
simu_IQR("Normal", 10,1000,1000)
simu_IQR("Exponential", 10,1000,1000)

Result: Comparing to the IQR with the inbuilt functions, the mean square error of IQR via resampling method of N(0,1) are lower than that of Exp(1). Also, the variability of their empirical versions of N(0,1) is also lower than that of exp(1). But generally, the biases are small.

2.2 Second

Q: Find a 95% confidence interval for the IQR and investigate its coverage probability using nsim = 10000 and nboot = 1000 simulation and bootstrap runs for both distributions with sample sizes n \(\in\) {10, 20, 30, 40}

A:

simu_IQR_CI <- function(Dist,n,nsim,nboot){
  
  # Create some containers
  erg <- c()
  IQR_var <- c()
  IQR <- c()
  lower <- c()
  upper <- c()
  
  # Generate data from different distributions
  if(Dist == "Normal") {
    x <- matrix(rnorm(n*nsim, mean = 0, sd = 1),ncol = nsim)
    IQR_std <- diff(qnorm(c(0.25, 0.75), mean = 0, sd = 1))
  }
  if(Dist == "Exponential") {
    x <- matrix((rexp(n = n*nsim, rate = 1) - 1) / sqrt(1), ncol = nsim)
    IQR_std <- diff(qexp(c(0.25, 0.75),rate = 1))
  }
  
  # Helping Matrix for Non-parametric Bootstrap
  B <- apply(matrix(1:n, ncol = nboot, nrow = n), 2, sample, replace = TRUE)
  
  # Bootstrap
  for(i in 1:nsim){
    xi <- x[,i]
    xstar <- matrix(xi[B], ncol = nboot, nrow = n)
    IQR_star <- apply(xstar,2,IQR)
    IQR[i] <- mean(IQR_star)
    
    # Compute 95% CI
    lower[i] <- quantile(IQR_star,0.025)
    upper[i] <- quantile(IQR_star,0.975)
    erg[i] <- ((lower[i] < IQR_std) && (upper[i] > IQR_std))
  }
  
  # Display the results
  result <- data.frame(Dist = Dist, n = n, IQR_boot_mean = round(mean(IQR),6), lowerCI = round(mean(lower),6), upperCI = round(mean(upper),6), coverage_p = mean(erg))
  write.table(result, row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE, append = TRUE)
  return(result)
}

nsim <- 1000
nboot <- 1000
n <- c(10,20,30,40)
Dist <- c("Normal","Exponential")
set.seed(1)
for(h in 1:length(n)){
  for(i in 1:length(Dist)){
      simu_IQR_CI(Dist[i],n[h],nsim,nboot)
  }
}

Result: Generally, the larger the data set, the higher the coverage probability. According to the coverage probability, the test of N(0,1) is more conservative than that of Exp(1).

4 Question 4

Consider paired data \(X_k = (X_{1k};X_{2k}), k = 1,...,n\) and \(X_{ik} \sim F_i, i = 1, 2\) with \(F_i\) being any distribution function. Furthermore, we define the relative (marginal) treatment effect as

\(p = P(X_{11} < X_{22}) + \frac{1}{2}P(X_{11} = X_{22}).\)

4.1 First

Q: Explain the model in detail and state the underlying assumptions.

A: If we consider i=1 as group1, i=2 as group2, group1 and group2 are normally based on the same observations but in different conditions or time points. Thus, they might come from different distributions. In this model, we aim to implement a comparison between such paired-groups.

Underlying assumptions:

  • data is ordinal, and in this case, comparison of means is inappropriate
  • data is paired; Hence, they are not independent

4.2 Second

Q: Explain in your own words how the relative effect p can be interpreted.

A: The relative effect p could be interpreted as %(group1 < group2) +(1/2)%(group1 = group2), which measures whether values are different between the groups.

  • if p<0.5: Group1 tends to be larger than Group2

  • if p>0.5: Group1 tends to be smaller than Group2

  • if p=0.5: No tendency to smaller or larger values

4.3 Third

Q: Give three examples of research questions that could be answered with the relative effect p.

A:

  • What is the probability that men are taller than women?

  • What is the probability, blood pressure under treatment is higher than under control?

  • What is the impact of a treatment program? e.g. the difference of mental well being of participants between their first meeting and after 3 months on an ordinal scale with 1 = very happy and 10 = very unhappy

4.4 Fourth

Q: We are interested in estimating p and in particular finding a 95% confidence interval thereof. Propose three different ways and compare the methods in a simulation study in the following setups:

  • Use normal and log-normally distributed data.

  • Use the sample sizes \(n \in \{10, 20, 30 \}\).

  • Set the covariance matrices to:

$ _1 = \[\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0\\ 0 & 1 \\\end{pmatrix}\] $, $ _2 = \[\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0\\ 0 & 2 \\\end{pmatrix}\] $, and $ _3 = \[\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0.8\\ 0.8 & 2 \\\end{pmatrix}\]

$.

A:

# Clear the environment
rm(list = ls())

library(mvtnorm, quietly = TRUE)

# Inside the function, nperm and nboot are both set to 10000
testdifference <- function(n, Dist, sigma, nsim){
  mu = c(0,0)
  n1 <- n+1
  n2 <- 2*n
  x <- matrix(0,ncol = nsim,nrow = n2)
  for(i in 1:nsim){
    # Generate paired data
    if (Dist == "Normal") {
      xd <- rmvnorm(n = n, mean = mu, sigma = sigma)
    }
    if (Dist == "LogNor") {
      xd <- exp(rmvnorm(n = n, mean = mu, sigma = sigma))
    }

    xstar <- matrix(xd[, 1], nrow = n)
    ystar <- matrix(xd[, 2], nrow = n)
    
    x[,i] = rbind(xstar,ystar)
  }

  
  # Munzel test
  tcrit <- qt(0.975,n-1)
  x1 <- x[1:n,]
  x2 <- x[n1:n2,]
  
  # Overall ranks
  rx <- apply(x, 2, rank)
  
  rx1 <- colMeans(rx[1:n,])
  rx2 <- colMeans(rx[n1:n2,])
  
  phat <- 1/(2*n)*(rx1-rx2)+1/2
  
  # Calculate internal ranks
  rix1 <- apply(x1,2,rank)
  rix2 <- apply(x2,2,rank)
  
  BM1 <- 1/n*(rx1-rix1)
  BM2 <- 1/n*(rx2-rix2)
  
  BM3 <- BM1-BM2
  BM4 <- 1/(2*n)*(rx1-rx2)
  pd <- colMeans(BM2)
  m <- colMeans(BM3)
  
  # Variance estimator
  v <- (colSums(BM3^2)-n*m^2)/(n-1)
  
  # Confidence interval
  SE <- sqrt(v)/sqrt(n)
  Lower_Munzel <- phat - tcrit*SE
  Upper_Munzel <- phat + tcrit*SE

  # Permutation

  # Number of permutations
  nperm <- 100
    
  # Permutation matrix
  P <- matrix(0, nrow = (2*n), ncol = nperm)
  for(h in 1:nperm){
    P[,h] <- c(t(apply(cbind(1:n,(n+1):(2*n)),1,sample)))
  }
  
  Lower_p <- c()
  Upper_p <- c()
  
  for(s in 1:nsim){
    xs <- x[,s] #the sth column of x
    rs <- rx[,s] #the sth colum of the rank of x
    
    # Permute raw data
    xperm <- matrix(xs[P],nrow = n2,ncol = nperm)
    
    # Permute ranks
    rxperm <- matrix(rs[P],nrow = n2,ncol = nperm)
    
    # Permuted data in both "groups"
    xperm1 <- xperm[1:n,]
    xperm2 <- xperm[n1:n2,]
    
    # Permuted ranks in both "groups"
    rperm1 <- rxperm[1:n,]
    rperm2 <- rxperm[n1:n2,]
    
    # Internal ranks within the "groups"
    riperm1 <- apply(xperm1,2,rank)
    riperm2 <- apply(xperm2,2,rank)
    
    BMperm2 <- 1/n*(rperm2-riperm2)
    BMperm3 <- 1/n*(rperm1-riperm1)-BMperm2
    
    # Relative effect (Permutation version)
    pdperm <- colMeans(BMperm2)
    mperm3 <- colMeans(BMperm3)
    vperm3 <- (colSums(BMperm3^2)-n*mperm3^2)/(n-1)
    vperm30 <- (vperm3==0)
    vperm3[vperm30] <- 1/n
    
    # Permutation Test Statistic
    Tperm <- sqrt(n)*(pdperm-1/2)/sqrt(vperm3)
    
    # Confidence interval
    Lower_p[s] <- mean(mean(pdperm) + quantile(Tperm, 0.025)[[1]]*SE)
    Upper_p[s] <- mean(mean(pdperm) + quantile(Tperm, 0.975)[[1]]*SE)
  }  
   
  #Wild bootstrap
  
  nboot <- 100
  
  # Generate random weights
  WN <- matrix(rnorm(nboot*2*n), nrow = 2*n, ncol = nboot)
  
  mx <- colMeans(x)
  
  # Center data
  mxmat <- matrix(mx, nrow = 2*n, ncol = nsim, byrow = TRUE)
  zmat <- x - mxmat
  
  zrmat <- rx 
  
  Lower_w <- c()
  Upper_w <- c()
  
  for (i in 1:nsim) {
    ztemp <- matrix(zmat[, i], nrow = 2*n, ncol = nboot)
    zrtemp <- matrix(zrmat[, i], nrow = 2*n, ncol = nboot)
    
    # Generate WB resampling data
    xwild <- matrix(WN * ztemp,nrow = n2,ncol = nboot)
    
    # Generate WB resampling ranks
    rxwild <- matrix(zrtemp ,nrow = n2,ncol = nboot)
    
    # Permuted data in both "groups"
    xwild1 <- xwild[1:n,]
    xwild2 <- xwild[n1:n2,]
    
    # Permuted ranks in both "groups"
    rwild1 <- rxwild[1:n,]
    rwild2 <- rxwild[n1:n2,]
    
    # Internal ranks within the "groups"
    riwild1 <- apply(xwild1,2,rank)
    riwild2 <- apply(xwild2,2,rank)
    
    BMwild2 <- 1/n*(rwild2-riwild2)
    BMwild3 <- 1/n*(rwild1-riwild1)-BMwild2
    
    # Relative effect (Permutation version)
    pdwild <- colMeans(BMwild2)
    mwild3 <- colMeans(BMwild3)
    vwild3 <- (colSums(BMwild3^2)-n*mwild3^2)/(n-1)
    vwild30 <- (vwild3==0)
    vwild3[vwild30] <- 1/n
    
    # Permutation Test Statistic
    Twild <- sqrt(n)*(pdwild-1/2)/sqrt(vwild3)
    
    # Confidence interval
    Lower_w[i] <- mean(mean(pdwild) + quantile(Twild, 0.025)[[1]]*SE)
    Upper_w[i] <- mean(mean(pdwild) + quantile(Twild, 0.975)[[1]]*SE)
  }
    
    # Display the results
    result <- data.frame(Dist = Dist, n = n, p_Munzel = round(mean(phat),6), CI_Munzel_L = round(mean(Lower_Munzel),6), CI_Munzel_U=round(mean(Upper_Munzel),6), p_permute = round(mean(pdperm),6), CI_permute_L = round(mean(Lower_p),6), CI_permute_U = round(mean(Upper_p),6), p_wild = round(mean(pdwild),6), CI_wild_L = round(mean(Lower_w),6),CI_wild_U = round(mean(Upper_w),6))
    write.table(result, row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE, append = TRUE)
    return(result)
}


nsim <- 100
n <- c(10,20,30)
Dist <- c("Normal","LogNor")

set.seed(1)
for(h in 1:length(n)){
  for(hh in 1:length(Dist)){
    testdifference(n[h],Dist[hh],diag(2),nsim)
    testdifference(n[h],Dist[hh],diag(c(1,2)),nsim)
    testdifference(n[h],Dist[hh],diag(c(1,2)) + 0.8 * (1 - diag(2)),nsim)
  }
}

4.5 Fifth

Q: Present and interpret your results. Which method would you recommend? State your conclusion in 1-2 sentences.

A: Because we set means are equal, p should be 1/2 no matter how covariance varies. From the result of normal Munzel test ,permutation test and wild bootstrap test, we could see that the permutation one is more stable with \(\hat{p}\) being around 1/2 and its confidence interval is narrower than normal Munzel’s. Therefore, I recommend the permutation method.

6 Question 6

Consider independent samples \(X_{ik} = F_i, i = 1,...,a, k = 1,...,n_i\) with \(E(X_{ik}) = \mu_i\) and \(Var(X_{ik}) = {\sigma_i}^2\).

We are interested in testing the null hypothesis

\(H_0: C\pmb{\mu} = 0\)

with an arbitrary contrast matrix \(C\). Here \(\pmb{\mu} = (\mu_1,...,\mu_a)'\) denotes the vector of expectations.

6.1 First

Q: Explain the model in detail and state the underlying assumptions as well how the parameters are estimated.

A: In this statistical model, samples are independent in each class (\(a\) classes in total). Each class has its sample size \(n_i, i =1,...,a\), mean \(\mu_i, i =1,...,a\) and variance \(\sigma_i^2, i =1,...,a\). We are interested in multiple comparisons, so we assign the contrast matrix \(C\) to describe the pattern of the alternative \(H_1\). If \(H_0\) cannot be rejected, then there is no difference in all kinds of comparisons described in \(C\). In other words, we have many comparison tasks and they could be represented in a contrast matrix \(C\). The means and variances of all classes could be estimated by their empirical means and variances respectively.

  • Mean: \(\bar{\pmb{X}.} = (\bar{X_{1.}},...,\bar{X_{a.}})'\)

  • Variance: \(s^2_i = \frac{1}{n_i-1}\sum_{k=1}^{n_i}(X_{ik}-\bar{X_{i.}})^2\)

6.2 Second

Q: Propose a multiple contrast test procedure to test the null hypothesis.

A: First, we define our model and hypothesis, and set a suitable contrast matrix X. Second, we estimate the means, variances, variance of a contrast, and use these estimators to build our statistics in all comparisons. If any of the statistics are enough to reject \(H_0\), then we could spot it and distinguish which null hypothesis could be rejected according to our result. Also, we would use the distribution of the maximum value \(T_0\) to compute the critical value for the maximum of absolute value of statistics. Finally, we draw a conclusion based on our result.

6.3 Third

Q: Propose and explain the nonparametric and parametric bootstrap strategies for testing the null hypothesis.

A: Our goal of using resampling methods is to improve the approximation/method, i.e. to approximate the distribution of the maximum, since the original method is a multiple t-test and it might be liberal or conservative in case of small samples.

Both nonparametric and parametric bootstrap will generate resampling variables from our original data, and reassign the new data to different classes respectively. Then we compute empirical means and empirical variances with the resampling variables. Based on these, we could compute the vector of test statistics and get the maximum from them. Repeat the above nboot times and estimate the \((1-\alpha)\) quantile from all the maximums. At the end we will use it to test our null hypothesis.

The only difference between nonparametric and parametric bootstrap is how we generate the resampling variables. The former one draws with replacement from original fixed values; the latter randomly draw observations from \(N(0,\hat{s_i}^2)\)

6.4 Fourth

Q: Conduct a simulation study to assess the type-I error rates of the procedures at 5% level of significance.

  • Simulate normal, log-normal and exponentially distributed data.
  • Set the number of groups to a = 3.
  • Investigate balanced \(n_i \equiv n = 30\) as well as unbalanced designs with n1 = 20, n2 = 25, n3 = 30.
  • Set the variance to \(\sigma_i^2 = 1 \forall i \in{1,...,a)}\) and to\(\sigma_1^2 = 1, \sigma_2^2 = 1.5,\sigma_3^2 = 2\).
  • Use the Tukey-type contrast matrix \(C\).

A:

# Clear the environment
rm(list = ls())

library(multcomp,quietly = TRUE)

mySimulation <- function(a, n, s, cont, dist, nsim, nboot){
  
  # Result vector
  p0 <- c()
  p1 <- c()
  p2 <- c()
  
  # Number of observations per group
  if(n == "1") nii <- rep(30,a)
  if(n == "2") nii <- c(20,25,30)
  
  # Identical variances or estimated variances from previous exercise
  if(s == "1") sigma2 <- rep(1,a)
  if(s == "2") sigma2 <- c(1,1.5,2)
  
  # Contrast Matrix
  C <- matrix(contrMat(nii, type = cont), ncol = a)
  nc <- nrow(C)
  
  # Number of all observations
  N <- sum(nii)
  
  # Data generation
  vvec <- c()
  gp <- c()
  i <- 1
  while (i <= a) {
    vvec <- c(vvec, rep(sigma2[i], nii[i]))
    gp <- c(gp, rep(i, nii[i]))
    i <- i + 1
  }
  
  # Simulate the standardized data
  if (dist == "Normal") {
    x0 <- matrix(rnorm(N*nsim), ncol = nsim)
  }
  
  if(dist == "Lognormal"){
    x0 <- matrix(((exp(rnorm(n = N*nsim, mean = 0, sd = 1)) - exp(1/2)) / sqrt(exp(1)*(exp(1)-1))), ncol = nsim)
  }
  
  if(dist == "Exp"){
    x0 <- matrix(rexp(N*nsim)-1, ncol = nsim)
  }
  
  # Assigning variances
  x <- vvec*x0
  
  gp <- as.factor(gp)
  
  # Start of Simulation
  for (j in 1:nsim) {
    # Subsetting 
    Data_v <- data.frame(XV=x[, j], grp=gp)
    
    # Calculating means and variances of contrasts
    vmean <- aggregate(XV~grp,data = Data_v, mean)[,2]
    vvar <- aggregate(XV~grp,data = Data_v, var)[,2]
    vmat <- diag(vvar/nii)
    Cmu <- C%*%vmean
    CV <- C%*%vmat%*%t(C)
    
    # Correlation Matrix
    R <- cov2cor(CV)
    
    # Degree of freedom
    nul <- sapply(1:nrow(C),function(arg){c(t(C[arg,])%*%vmat%*%C[arg,])^2/sum(C[arg,]^4*vvar^2/(nii^2*(nii-1)))})
    nu <- round(min(nul))
    
    # Test statistic
    TT <- Cmu / sqrt(c(diag(CV)))
    T0 <- max(abs(TT))
    
    pval <- 1 - pmvt(lower = -T0, upper = T0, delta = rep(0, nc), df = nu, corr = R)[1]
    p0[j] <- (pval < 0.05)
    
    # First nonparametric
    NP <- c()
    TlNP <- matrix(rep(0,a*nboot), ncol = nboot)
    
    for(h in 1:nboot){
      if(length(unique(nii))==1){
        n0 <- unique(nii)
    # Draw with replacement from data, observation-wise
        ind <- sample(c(1:n0),n0,replace = TRUE)
      
        XNP1 <- Data_v[1:n0,1][ind]
        XNP2 <- Data_v[(n0+1):(2*n0),1][ind]
        XNP3 <- Data_v[(2*n0+1):(3*n0),1][ind]
        XNP <- data.frame(XN=c(XNP1,XNP2,XNP3), grp=gp)
      }else{
      # Draw with replacement from data, non-observation-wise
        ind1 <- sample(c(1:nii[1]),nii[1],replace = TRUE)
        ind2 <- sample(c(1:nii[2]),nii[2],replace = TRUE)
        ind3 <- sample(c(1:nii[3]),nii[3],replace = TRUE)
  
        XNP1 <- Data_v[1:nii[1],1][ind1]
        XNP2 <- Data_v[(nii[1]+1):(nii[1]+nii[2]),1][ind2]
        XNP3 <- Data_v[(nii[1]+nii[2]+1):(nii[1]+nii[2]+nii[3]),1][ind3]
        XNP <- data.frame(XN=c(XNP1,XNP2,XNP3), grp=gp)
      }
      
      XbarNP <- aggregate(XN~grp,data = XNP, mean)[,2]
      VhatNP <- aggregate(XN~grp,data = XNP, var)[,2]

      VmatNP <- diag(VhatNP/nii)

      CXNP <- C%*%(XbarNP-vmean)
      CVNPC <- C%*%VmatNP%*%t(C)

      TlNP[,h] <- CXNP / sqrt(c(diag(CVNPC)))
      NP[h] <- max(abs(TlNP[,h]))
    }
    # pvalue
    p1[j] = mean(NP>=T0)
    
    # parametric
    P <- c()
    TlP <- matrix(rep(0,a*nboot), ncol = nboot)
    s2vec<-rep(vvar,nii)
    
    for(h in 1:nboot){
      
      # Draw new samples according to their empirical variances
      XP <- rnorm(N,0,sqrt(s2vec))
      DatP <- data.frame(XP, grp=gp)
      
      XbarP <- aggregate(XP~grp,data = DatP, mean)[,2]
      si2P <- aggregate(XP~grp,data = DatP, var)[,2]
      ShatP <- diag(si2P/nii)
      CXP <- C%*%XbarP
      CVPC <- C%*%ShatP%*%t(C)

      TlP[,h] <-CXP / sqrt(c(diag(CVPC)))
      P[h] <- max(abs(TlP[,h]))
    }

    # pvalue
    p2[j] <- mean(P >= T0)
   }
  result <- data.frame(n = n, a = a, s = s, Dist = dist, Cont = cont,p_T = mean(p0),  p_nonparametric = mean(p1<0.05), p_parametric = mean(p2<0.05))
  print(result)
}

n <- c("1","2")
s <- c("1","2")
d <- c("Normal", "Lognormal", "Exp")

set.seed(1)
for(h in 1:length(d)){
  for(hh in 1:length(n)){
    for(hhh in 1:length(s)){
      mySimulation(a = 3, n = n[hh], s = s[hhh], cont = "Tukey", dist = d[h], nsim = 100, nboot = 100)
    }
  }
}

6.5 Fifth

Q: Present and interpret your results. When are the methods applicable? State your conclusion in 1-2 sentences.

A: When the data is unbalanced and variances differ, all the three methods work well; the nonparametric method is generally more stable and conservative, and it works pretty good especially when data are from lognormal distribution; parametric method performs better when the unbalanced data comes from the normal distribution
